So, please, fill out the Free/Reduced Lunch applications so that you may continue to get free or reduced priced meals if you qualify.

Thank you.

To Parents and Students Coming Into the High School for Orientation Tonight:

Just a few reminders before you come to the building this evening:

1. Please remember to bring a face covering and practice social distancing while you are in the building. School policies of wearing a face covering and making sure to stay 6 feet apart from others will be enforced at orientation tonight.

2. Remember that only one parent is allowed in the building with your new to high school student.

3. We will be handing out laptops to new to high school students tonight. As part of our technology policy for school devices, families will be required to pay $35 per device in order for students to use it throughout the school year. This money will pay for insurance on the device that will cover any damage or other problems that may happen to the device throughout the school year. If you will have trouble paying the $35, please talk with Mr. Woitalewicz.

Thanks, and again, we look forward to seeing you tonight!

Mr. Woitalewicz

HS Principal

WWG Schools

Safe Learning Plan Guide for Families
MDE has created a Family Guide to Minnesota’s Safe Learning Plan available now in English, Hmong, Karen, Somali and Spanish. This guide provides an overview of the safe learning plan, and includes information on the role of schools, MDE and the Minnesota Department of Health.

Earlier this summer, we developed a Family Guide to the 2020-21 School Year Planning Guidance, which expands on each of the learning models and provides information about attendance, nutrition, transportation, student and family support and more. This guide is also available in English, Hmong, Karen, Somali and Spanish.

WWG FFA Chapter To Be Featured on RFD-TV!

Westbrook Walnut Grove, MN – The WWG FFA Chapter from Westbrook High School will be showcased this weekend, July 4-5, 2020, on “This Week In AgriBusiness”, a weekly, one-hour television agri-news program hosted by two of the country’s most well-known farm broadcasters Max Armstrong and Orion Samuelson.

The WWG FFA Chapter Tribute will include information about the chapter’s history, activities and community service. It also includes several photos of the students and their participation in chapter activities.

Viewers can see the WWG FFA Chapter Tribute during “This Week In AgriBusiness” which is aired on RFD-TV, a 24-hour television network for rural America. RFD-TV is carried on Dish Network channel 231 and on DirecTV channel 345, as well as a number of other cable systems. “This Week In AgriBusiness” airs three times on RFD-TV throughout the weekend. Broadcast times are 7:00a.m. on Saturday; 5:00a.m. and 9:30p.m. on Sundays; (Central Time Zone).

post_text:
Parents have planned a parade route for senior graduates directly following graduation on May 31st.

Here is a picture of the route through four different towns. A copy will be in this weekend's edition of the Cottonwood County Shopper, with many thanks to their graphics department for putting this map pdf together.

The parade train will start in Westbrook, head to Walnut Grove, then Revere, and finish in Storden. Make sure to come out to the parade route (while maintaining proper social distance) and support our seniors on the 31st after their graduation ceremony!

The graduation ceremony starts at 2pm with the parade following directly after. Live updates will be posted to our Facebook page on the location of the parade train and approximate times they will arrive in each town.

Attention High School Parents and Students:

High School teachers will not be posting new assignments for the next four school days (April 29 and 30, May 1 and 4).

We are asking high school students to use this time to work on current missing assignments if they have any. Students, please take the time to do so.

Teachers are taking this time to regularly check, grade, and provide feedback on student work and to reach out and offer help to any student who might be struggling. Do not hesitate to contact teachers at this time as they will be readily available to help with any questions students or parents may have.

We are hoping this time allows many of our students to catch their breath, get caught up on assignments, and feel better prepared for the next few weeks to end the school year.

From Margaret at Mary & Martha’s Pantry to school and community families:

We are open with the same hours for service. The only difference is that we are outside service only. My number is on this flyer- Please share as we want the community to know that we are here for them during these times & always.

Please reach out to me if you have any questions- UCAP is offering delivery service through our transportation program for those homebound, elderly, or with no car. At this time we are delaying our Open House for the Community until things settle down.

Thanks again so much-I know these times are tough on the school employees & kids too.



Take Care & hope all are healthy!

post_text:
Good evening school families. While as a district we are waiting on more definitive information from the Minnesota Department of Education, we can provide some basic information to all of you. Starting Monday, March 30th distance learning will start for our students and run at least until April 30th. Parents, please check your emails tomorrow for more detailed information regarding distance learning. We will still continue to offer childcare for children of essential workers as well as offer meals for our students up to age 18. Please contact the school office if you are in need of meals or childcare beginning next week.

Thank you,

Loy Woelber, Superintendent of Westbrook Walnut Grove #2898, Fulda #505 and Lake Benton #404

WWG Elementary Distance Learning
Material Pick-up

Thursday, March 26 (3:00-6:00pm)
@ WWG Elementary

In preparation for the start of Distance Learning, we will be distributing materials to all elementary students at the Walnut Grove school. We are requesting ONE parent (no children) from each family to collect materials and respect social distancing by using the cones while waiting in line. Materials will be distributed at all three doors on the north side of the building. Doors will be labeled according to the last name of the oldest child (PreK-6) in each family. Materials that are not picked up on Thursday (3:00-6:00) will be available on Friday from 11:30-12:30.

Last Name A-K (Office Door)
Last Name L-V (Middle Library Door)
Last Name W-Z (Gym Door)

If you have questions, please contact a member of the Distance Learning Committee (Mr. Jenniges, Mrs. Quade, Mrs. Locke) at school or your child’s classroom teacher.

Thank You,

WWG Elementary

post_text: Congratulations to our robotics team as they end the Lake Superior Regional competition in 4th place. They advanced to the semifinal round of the competition before getting beat out by a very competitive group led by the robotics team from Edina. WWG’s ranking at this competition most likely means that they have punched a second straight ticket to state, but that will not become official until all regional competitions have been completed. Overall a great weekend for our robotics team! Pictured is our “drive team” of Jonathan, Luke, Colton, and TJ.

post_text: On Friday, February 28, 2020, The Earth YES Class challenged WWG HS students to go a day without their phones. The goal of Earth YES is to save energy but we also wanted to push the WWG student body to interact more and actually look up in the hallways instead of using their phones as a safety valve to avoid eye contact. Altogether we had seventy phones, with nine of them being teachers and paraprofessionals and the rest being our student body.

post_text:
WWG/RRC Speech team went to compete last Saturday (2/15) in Luverne. And compete they did, bringing home the 3rd in the Large Teams division. 257 students competed from18 different schools. Students receive individual points for their placement in their own categories. Those points are then added together to determine who receives the trophies.

Tesa Meier had a great day and brought home 1st place in Drama. Also in Drama, Elizabeth Wiggins earned 5th place and Jaden Olson came in 10th. We had a good day in Poetry as well with Jaden Scholl taking 2nd and Adri Ruiz taking 3rd. Alexis Starnes earned a 6th place in Creative Expression. In Lexie Weber’s first meet this season, she came away with 5th place in Extemporaneous Reading. Caitlin Mershon earned 5th in Extemporaneous Speaking. Students have worked hard and it shows.

post_text:
WWG/RRC JH speech students did well in their first Jr. High tournament. It was hosted by the Tracy Panthers. We had 4 students competing in 3 categories. Caitlin Mershon received 3rd place in Extemp Speaking and Theresa Nwaiga took 8th in Prose. Both Mariah Bryant and Tim Kleeberger wove their tales in Storytelling with Mariah taking home 5th place honors. So proud of our junior high students.
Two students from our varsity team, Alexis Starnes and Ethan Price, got an opportunity to be on the other side of the table, to judge a competition. This gives our competitors more understanding of the role judges play and how they can make improvements in their own speeches. They each presided over two rounds of competition. Both students found it to be harder than they thought. “It was so hard to pick one over another. They were all so good,” remarked Alexis. “I just want to help them be better,” stated Ethan. “I will come back and judge for you after I graduate anytime.” - Mrs. Caygle

post_text: Congrats to Jace on his victory at the Red River Riot over Christmas break! Jace had the largest bracket of the tournament with 28. 6 in the bracket were state ranked. He defeated 3 that were unbeaten coming in to the tournament. The last two matches were against a wrestler that committed to Augustana and a wrestler that committed to Concordia. Way to go Jace!

post_text: Students in Mrs. Dibble’s Algebra 2 class were busy this week making gingerbread houses. They created scale drawings of their homes, figured out construction costs, and found the price per square inch. Santa’s beach house was the winner!
